<page id="Classifiers" count="3/3">
    <title level="2">Overall Typology Questions - Noun Classes and Classifiers</title>
    <introduction>Some languages have a system of noun classes that marks nouns by their shape, position, or other characteristics.  In many of these languages, the class marking becomes an agreement system that requires concord throughout the nominal phrase and even with the verb.  Therefore, <technicalTermRef term="ttQuantifiers"/>, <technicalTermRef term="ttArticles"/>, <technicalTermRef term="ttDemonstratives"/>, adjectives, and verbs may need to be marked with the appropriate noun class marker.
       <br/><br/>
       The Bantu languages spoken in Africa represent perhaps the best known noun class system.  These languages have up to 22 distinct classes, which are represented by numbers.  About half of them are for singular nouns only and an equal number for plural nouns only.  Others are for mass or abstract nouns or locations.  
       Examples from Sesotho, a Bantu language spoken primarily in South Africa are given here, with (1) showing the concord noun class agreement through both the subject and object nominal phrases and (2) showing the use of the noun class marker on the verb for both subject and object when the nominal phrases are pronominalized. (Data from Demuth, K. 2000. Bantu noun class systems: Loan word and acquistion evidence of semantic productivity.  In G. Senft (ed.), Classification Systems.  Cambridge University Press:270-292.) 
    </introduction>
