   <introduction>A simpler type of classifier system is illustrated in examples (8-10) from Ayutla Mixtec, spoken in southern Mexico.  In this language, there are classifier prefixes derived from either a generic noun or a pronoun that appear on most nouns that refer to animals or insects, or to liquids, trees or objects made of wood, or objects that are basically round.  In Mixtec, there is no concord classifier agreement within the nominal phrase or sentence, so these prefixes only show up on the nouns and might be considered more <technicalTermRef term="ttDerivational"/>.  There are, however, similar distinctions in the third person pronouns that refer to them.  Mixtec uses types rather than numbers to identify the classifiers. Some of the noun roots are identifiable as other words, but some are indeterminate elements. (Data from Hills, Robert. 1990. A Syntactic Sketch of Ayutla Mixtec.  In Bradley, C. Henry and Barbara E. Hollenbach, (eds.) Studies in the Syntax of Mixtecan Languages. Vol.2. The Summer Institute of Linguistics and The University of Texas at Arlington:Dallas. 200-201.)</introduction>
